        <name>7.4.4.2 Inverse of a 3 x 3 matrix &#9472; determinant method</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Use the determinant method to find the inverse of the
following matrices&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[A = {@A@},\] \[B = {@B@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(A^{-1} = \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(B^{-1} = \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;To find the inverse of \(A = {@A@}\) using the determinant method will require four steps.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First we find the determinant of \(A\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\[ \det(A) = {@detA@}. \]&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since \(\det(A) \neq 0\) the inverse of \(A\) exists.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, we replace each element of \(A\) by its cofactor.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cofactor of \({A}_{ij}\) is the determinant of the matrix that remains when row \(i\) and column \(j\) are
    removed, multiplied by \((-1)^{i+j}\). So we have,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;{@cofactorsA@}.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then we transpose the result to obtain the adjoint matrix:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(\mathrm{adj}(A) = {@cofactorsA@}^{T} = {@adjA@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally we obtain \(A^{-1}\) using the following formula:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\det(A)} \mathrm{adj}(A) = \frac{1}{@detA@} {@adjA@} = {@ta1@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The method can be used to determine \(B^{-1}\) similarly, which gives \( B^{-1} = {@ta2@}.\)&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
